Modelling histone modification and gene expression

Zhigang Lu
20.08.2019

Aim

Trying to model the relationship between histone modification levels (ChIP-Seq) and gene expression (RNA-Seq).

Modelling has been done in the past

Using tag counts from ChIP-Seq

(2010 PNAS) Histone modification levels are predictive for gene expression

  • used linear model on full or different combinations of modifications ([-2k, +2k] around TSS)
  • r = 0.77 on full model
  • using a single modification model can predict with r = 0.72

(2012 Genome Bio) Modeling gene expression using chromatin features in various cellular contexts

  • data from ENCODE
  • used two-setp modelling (Random Forest and linear regression) on 81 bins in three regions: around TSS, gene body, around TES
  • achieved Pearson r = 0.9 and RMSE = 1.9

Distribution of histone modifications

(Zhang et al 2015 EMBO Reports)

So I picked regions for each mark: 

Activative
- H3K4me3: -200 ...TSS... middle of gene (nearTSS)
- H4K20me1: -200...TSS... middle of gene (nearTSS)
- H3K9ac: gene body (Smv7.2.genes)
- H3K23ac: gene body (Smv7.2.genes)
- H3K36me3: middle of gene...TES...+200 (towardsTES)

Repressive
- H3K9me3: -2000...TSS...+200 (promoter)
- H3K27me3: -200...TSS... middle of gene (nearTSS)

Histone modification levels

  • pepole normally used tag counts

Just for testing, I counted the occurance of peaks using bedtools intersect from the two files:

combined_mode-differential_binsize150_stepsize75_combinations_BsOv.bed combined_mode-differential_binsize150_stepsize75_combinations_SsOv.bed

Would that make sense??

Input files for building machine learning models

So the input file for modelling looks like this:

id H3K9me3 H3K4me3 H4K20me1 H3K27me3 H3K9ac H3K23ac H3K36me3 rpkm_bO

Smp_000030 0 12 26 0 4 28 11 142.12030411154
Smp_000040 1 15 34 0 50 32 31 43.080410889657

Testing with different machine learning models

  • linear regression
  • support vecor regression
  • decision trees (rpart)
  • neural networks
  • random forests

used log2(rpkm_bO+1) as dependent variables

80% for training and 20% for testing

Model performance

Pearson's r between prediction and measurement

     linear       SVM     rpart        NN        RF
  0.5931168 0.3863685 0.6771356 0.7111849 0.7446014

So I took Random Forest for modelling, with 1000 trees.

RF model in bO


Call:
 randomForest(formula = log2(rpkm_bO + 1) ~ ., data = bO.train,      importance = TRUE, ntree = 1000) 
               Type of random forest: regression
                     Number of trees: 1000
No. of variables tried at each split: 2

          Mean of squared residuals: 3.623289
                    % Var explained: 54.72

54.68% of variance can be explained by the model, which is not bad.

Effect of pairing on histone marks

Pairing seems shifted the importance of H3K36me3 and H3K23ac, which is also an impression we obtained from several test genes.
